tables.description: The audit_checks table represents a record of regular checks performed on sites to ensure compliance and adherence to standards. It stores information about the site being audited, the date of the audit, the auditor's details, and the audit score obtained. This table is typically used in analytics and business workflows to track the performance of sites over time and identify areas for improvement.

columns.description: The audit_pk column represents a unique identifier for each audit check record, serving as a primary key for the table. It stores a unique integer value for each record. This column is crucial for tracking and referencing individual audit check records.

The site_fk column represents the foreign key referencing the site_master table, linking each audit check record to the corresponding site. It stores an integer value representing the site ID. This column enables the tracking of audit checks performed on specific sites.

The audit_dt column represents the date of the audit check, storing a date value for each record. It captures the timing of the audit check and helps track the performance of sites over time. This column is essential for analyzing audit check data and identifying trends.

The auditor column represents the name of the person performing the audit check, storing a character varying value for each record. It captures the identity of the auditor and helps track the audit process. This column is crucial for auditing and compliance purposes.

The audit_score column represents the score obtained during the audit check, storing an integer value for each record. It captures the outcome of the audit check and helps evaluate the performance of sites. This column is essential for tracking and analyzing audit check data.

tables.description: The event_log table stores a record of events that occur within an organization, including staff activities, system updates, and other significant occurrences. It captures information about the event category, risk level, and the staff member involved. This table is crucial for auditing, tracking, and analyzing organizational activities and identifying potential risks or issues.

columns.description: The event_pk column represents a unique identifier for each event log record, serving as a primary key for the table. It stores a unique integer value for each record. This column is crucial for tracking and referencing individual event log records.

The staff_fk column represents the foreign key referencing the staff table, linking each event log record to the corresponding staff member. It stores an integer value representing the staff ID. This column enables the tracking of events performed by specific staff members.

The event_dt column represents the date of the event, storing a date value for each record. It captures the timing of the event and helps track the activities of staff members. This column is essential for analyzing event log data and identifying trends.

The event_category column represents the category of the event, storing a character varying value for each record. It captures the type of event and helps track the activities of staff members. This column is crucial for auditing and compliance purposes.

The risk_level column represents the risk level associated with the event, storing an integer value for each record. It captures the severity of the event and helps evaluate the impact of staff activities. This column is essential for tracking and analyzing event log data.

tables.description: The learning_records table represents a record of courses completed by staff members, including the course name, completion date, and status. It stores information about the staff member's learning history and progress. This table is used in analytics and business workflows to track staff development, identify training needs, and measure the effectiveness of learning programs.

columns.description: The learning_pk column represents a unique identifier for each learning record, serving as a primary key for the table. It stores a unique integer value for each record. This column is crucial for tracking and referencing individual learning records.

The staff_fk column represents the foreign key referencing the staff table, linking each learning record to the corresponding staff member. It stores an integer value representing the staff ID. This column enables the tracking of learning activities performed by specific staff members.

The course_name column represents the name of the course completed by the staff member, storing a character varying value for each record. It captures the type of learning activity and helps track the learning history of staff members. This column is crucial for auditing and compliance purposes.

The course_dt column represents the date of the course completion, storing a date value for each record. It captures the timing of the learning activity and helps track the progress of staff members. This column is essential for analyzing learning record data and identifying trends.

The completion_status column represents the status of the course completion, storing a character varying value for each record. It captures the outcome of the learning activity and helps evaluate the effectiveness of learning programs. This column is essential for tracking and analyzing learning record data.

tables.description: The org_units table represents a record of organizational units within the organization, including their titles, site affiliations, and unit heads. It stores information about the structure and hierarchy of the organization. This table is typically used in analytics and business workflows to understand the organizational landscape, identify areas of responsibility, and track changes in the organizational structure.

columns.description: The unit_pk column represents a unique identifier for each organizational unit, serving as a primary key for the table. It stores a unique integer value for each record. This column is crucial for tracking and referencing individual organizational units.

The unit_title column represents the title of the organizational unit, storing a character varying value for each record. It captures the name of the unit and helps track the organizational structure. This column is crucial for auditing and compliance purposes.

The site_fk column represents the foreign key referencing the site_master table, linking each organizational unit to the corresponding site. It stores an integer value representing the site ID. This column enables the tracking of organizational units within specific sites.

The unit_head column represents the head of the organizational unit, storing a character varying value for each record. It captures the identity of the unit head and helps track the organizational hierarchy. This column is crucial for auditing and compliance purposes.

The created_on column represents the date of creation for the organizational unit, storing a timestamp value for each record. It captures the timing of the unit creation and helps track changes in the organizational structure. This column is essential for analyzing organizational unit data and identifying trends.

tables.description: The site_master table represents a record of sites operated by the organization, including their titles, locations, and creation dates. It stores information about the organization's physical presence and operations. This table is used in analytics and business workflows to track site performance, identify trends, and make informed decisions about site management and resource allocation.

columns.description: The site_pk column represents a unique identifier for each site, serving as a primary key for the table. It stores a unique integer value for each record. This column is crucial for tracking and referencing individual sites.

The site_title column represents the title of the site, storing a character varying value for each record. It captures the name of the site and helps track the organization's physical presence. This column is crucial for auditing and compliance purposes.

The nation column represents the nation where the site is located, storing a character varying value for each record. It captures the geographical location of the site and helps track the organization's global presence. This column is essential for analyzing site data and identifying trends.

The region column represents the region where the site is located, storing a character varying value for each record. It captures the geographical location of the site and helps track the organization's global presence. This column is essential for analyzing site data and identifying trends.

The created_on column represents the date of creation for the site, storing a timestamp value for each record. It captures the timing of the site creation and helps track changes in the organization's physical presence. This column is essential for analyzing site data and identifying trends.

tables.description: The staff table represents a record of staff members within the organization, including their full names, unit affiliations, roles, and joining dates. It stores information about the organization's human resources and personnel. This table is typically used in analytics and business workflows to track staff demographics, identify skills gaps, and measure staff turnover and retention rates.

columns.description: The staff_pk column represents a unique identifier for each staff member, serving as a primary key for the table. It stores a unique integer value for each record. This column is crucial for tracking and referencing individual staff members.

The staff_fullname column represents the full name of the staff member, storing a character varying value for each record. It captures the identity of the staff member and helps track the organization's human resources. This column is crucial for auditing and compliance purposes.

The unit_fk column represents the foreign key referencing the org_units table, linking each staff member to the corresponding organizational unit. It stores an integer value representing the unit ID. This column enables the tracking of staff members within specific organizational units.

The role_name column represents the role of the staff member, storing a character varying value for each record. It captures the job function of the staff member and helps track the organization's human resources. This column is crucial for auditing and compliance purposes.

The joining_date column represents the date of joining for the staff member, storing a date value for each record. It captures the timing of the staff member's employment and helps track staff turnover and retention rates. This column is essential for analyzing staff data and identifying trends.
